Issues.Body:
Created the default Razor Components Template with Visual Studio Preview 16.3 and .net Core preview 8. Edited the `NavBar.razor` component to show the user the state of a service. When the state has changed I try to Invoke the `StateHasChanged` method. But when I try to do so I get the following exception:

> Exception thrown: 'System.ArgumentException' in Microsoft.AspNetCore.Components.dll
> The renderer does not have a component with ID 5.

The code:

```
<div class="top-row pl-4 navbar navbar-dark">
	<a class="navbar-brand" href="">TecyardWorkbench @(mqttConnected ? "On" : "Off") </a>
	<button class="navbar-toggler" @onclick="ToggleNavMenu">
		<span class="navbar-toggler-icon"></span>
	</button>
</div>
//... the rest of the default NavBar.razor code
@code {
	bool collapseNavMenu = true;
	string NavMenuCssClass => collapseNavMenu ? "collapse" : null;
	bool mqttConnected;

	

	protected override void OnInitialized()
	{
		base.OnInitialized();//don't know if needed?
		//ugly implementation due to VS syntax error when trying to use FactoryStart
		new Task(async () =>
		{
			while (true)
			{
				await Task.Delay(1000);
				if (MqttService.Instance.Client.IsConnected != mqttConnected)
				{
					mqttConnected = MqttService.Instance.Client.IsConnected;
					await this.InvokeAsync(() => this.StateHasChanged()); //here throws the exception
				}
			}

		}).Start();
	}

	void ToggleNavMenu()
	{
		collapseNavMenu = !collapseNavMenu;
	}
}
```
